Global warming in context

“..increasing trends of historical heatwave frequency, duration and cumulative intensity..”

between 80ºC (Australia) and 240ºC (Western Russia) of cumulative heat experienced

Perkins-Kirkpatrick and Lewis (2020)

  • Heat exhaustion
  • Stroke
  • Increased risks for those with pre-existing conditions
  • 166,000 excess deaths between 1998 - 2017

although heat waves do not get as much attention as other natural disasters because there impacts are not immediately obvious, they do have significant impacts on human health

WHO (2023)

Solutions?

Mechanical Cooling

Pros

  • Easy to design for
  • Accepted in industry
  • Enabled increased productivity
  • Reliable

Cons

  • Susceptible to failure during heat waves

    • Loads increase when power system most vulnerable, leading to blackouts
    • In Shanghai, documented shortages greater than a 1 GWh 1

  • Energy intensive

    • AC + electric fan account for 20% of total energy use in buildings 2

  • Inaccesible

    • Ability to own an AC constrained by income 3
      • 99% of private apartments in Singapore have AC
      • Closer to 4% of households in India

  1. Liang et al. (2016)

  2. IEA (2018)

  3. IEA (2018)

Natural Cooling

Pros

  • Low operational energy

  • Accessible

  • Has worked well for some time

    • Modern AC unit invented in 1900 and only became popular in the US in the 1950s 1

Cons

  • Difficult to design for
  • Industry skepticism
  • Unreliable due to uncertainty
    • Occupant behavior
    • Outdoor climate

  1. IEA (2018)

Cooling “Tech”

Zhang et al. (2021)

Why Windows?

Climate and occupant uncertainty

  • What is the effect of window opening and closing on indoor climate?
  • How does this change with different building designs, occupant behavior, and outdoor climate?
  • How can practitioners access and leverage this information in the early stages of the design process?

Why Predicting W/O/C is Useful

  • Less invasive way of determining occupant actions

  • Understanding when windows are open, enables us to use to contextual information understand why they are open

    • D’Oca and Hong grouped occupants into 3-types: thermal-driven, time-driven, thermal+time driven 1

  • Inform design of naturally cooled buildings

  1. D’Oca and Hong (2014)

W/O/C Predictions since 1990…

timeline
    title History of Social Media Platform
    1990 : Fritsch : Markov chain models 
    1990 : Haldi and Robinson : Markov chain and logistic regression 
    1990 : Schweiker : Tests reveal performance affected by cultural changes
    1990 : Markovic : Bayesian and random forest regression 
    2023 : de Rautlin de Roy : review of machine learning performance and new metrics

D’Oca and Hong (2014)

Research Gaps

  • gaps:
    • long data collection periods: shorter periods are needed for practical use
    • only supervised models : unclear how coefficients/models transfer to radically different buildings in different climates

discussion of supervised vs not.

Analysis

Approach

Design an unsupervised method to predict window/open closing based on short periods of easily accesible data

Tools

  • Measurment
  • Time series analysis
  • Building energy modeling

instead of just listing tools, give a preview of what going to discuss

Measurement Technique

  • Data collected in adjacent rooms
  • Experimented with different window treatments
  • Affordable sensors

highlight that sensors used are affordable, and many modern buildings already monitor temperature as part of their operation

highlight that predicting the window opening close data as a function of temperature and that didnt colelct for very long periods of time
